# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rtl-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] A **gate equivalent** (**GE**) stands for a unit of measure which allows specifying *manufacturing-technology-independent complexity* of digital electronic circuits.
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] For today's CMOS technologies, the silicon area of a two-input drive-strength-one NAND gate usually constitutes the *technology-dependent* unit area commonly referred to as gate equivalent.
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] A specification in gate equivalents for a certain circuit reflects a complexity measure, from which a corresponding silicon area can be deduced for a dedicated manufacturing technology.
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] In digital circuit design, a dedicated *standard cell library* is employed for each manufacturing technology (e.g., CMOS).
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] The standard cell library comprises many different logic gates, for example a NAND gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] For each logical type of logic gate, e.g., a two-input NAND, there usually exist different physical realizations in the standard cell library, for instance with different output drive strengths.
[src:rtl-synthesis/gate-equivalent] Basically, a two-input drive-strength-one NAND gate in CMOS technology consists of four transistors.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In computer engineering, **logic synthesis** is a process by which an abstract specification of desired circuit behavior, typically at register transfer level (RTL), is turned into a design implementation in terms of logic gates, typically by a computer program called a *synthesis tool*.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Common examples of this process include synthesis of designs specified in hardware description languages, including VHDL and Verilog.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Some synthesis tools generate bitstreams for programmable logic devices such as PALs or FPGAs, while others target the creation of ASICs.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Logic synthesis is one step in circuit design in the electronic design automation, the others are place and route and verification and validation.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The roots of logic synthesis can be traced to the treatment of logic by George Boole (1815 to 1864), in what is now termed Boolean algebra.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In 1938, Claude Shannon showed that the two-valued Boolean algebra can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] In the early days, **logic design** involved manipulating the truth table representations as Karnaugh maps.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The Karnaugh map-based minimization of logic is guided by a set of rules on how entries in the maps can be combined.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] A human designer can typically only work with Karnaugh maps containing up to four to six variables.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The first step toward automation of logic minimization was the introduction of the Quine–McCluskey algorithm that could be implemented on a computer.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] This exact minimization technique presented the notion of prime implicants and minimum cost covers that would become the cornerstone of two-level minimization.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Nowadays, the much more efficient Espresso heuristic logic minimizer has become the standard tool for this operation.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Another area of early research was in state minimization and encoding of finite-state machines (FSMs), a task that was the bane of designers.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The applications for logic synthesis lay primarily in digital computer design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Hence, IBM and Bell Labs played a pivotal role in the early automation of logic synthesis.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The evolution from discrete logic components to programmable logic arrays (PLAs) hastened the need for efficient two-level minimization, since minimizing terms in a two-level representation reduces the area in a PLA.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Two-level logic circuits are of limited importance in a very-large-scale integration (VLSI) design; most designs use multiple levels of logic.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Almost any circuit representation in RTL or Behavioural Description is a multi-level representation.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] An early system that was used to design multilevel circuits was LSS from IBM.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] It used local transformations to simplify logic.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Work on LSS and the Yorktown Silicon Compiler spurred rapid research progress in logic synthesis in the 1980s.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Several universities contributed by making their research available to the public, most notably SIS from University of California, Berkeley, RASP from University of California, Los Angeles and BOLD from University of Colorado, Boulder.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Within a decade, the technology migrated to commercial logic synthesis products offered by electronic design automation companies.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The leading developers and providers of logic synthesis software packages are Synopsys, Cadence, and Siemens.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Their synthesis tools are Synopsys Design Compiler, Cadence First Encounter and Siemens Precision RTL.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Logic operations usually consist of Boolean AND, OR, XOR and NAND operations, and are the most basic forms of operations in an electronic circuit.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Arithmetic operations are usually implemented with the use of logic operators.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] With a goal of increasing designer productivity, research efforts on the synthesis of circuits specified at the behavioral level have led to the emergence of commercial solutions in 2004, which are used for complex ASIC and FPGA design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] These tools automatically synthesize circuits specified using high-level languages, like ANSI C/C++ or SystemC, to a register transfer level (RTL) specification, which can be used as input to a gate-level logic synthesis flow.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Typical practical implementations of a logic function utilize a multi-level network of logic elements.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Starting from an RTL description of a design, the synthesis tool constructs a corresponding multilevel Boolean network.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Next, this network is optimized using several technology-independent techniques before technology-dependent optimizations are performed.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The typical cost function during technology-independent optimizations is total literal count of the factored representation of the logic function (which correlates quite well with circuit area).
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Finally, technology-dependent optimization transforms the technology-independent circuit into a network of gates in a given technology.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] The simple cost estimates are replaced by more concrete, implementation-driven estimates during and after technology mapping.
[src:rtl-synthesis/logic-synthesis] Mapping is constrained by factors such as the available gates (logic functions) in the technology library, the drive sizes for each gate, and the delay, power, and area characteristics of each gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] In digital electronics, a **NAND** (**NOT AND**) **gate** is a logic gate which produces an output which is false only if all its inputs are true; thus its output is complement to that of an AND gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] A LOW (0) output results only if all the inputs to the gate are HIGH (1); if any input is LOW (0), a HIGH (1) output results.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] A NAND gate is made using transistors and junction diodes.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] By De Morgan's laws, a two-input NAND gate's logic may be expressed as ${\overline {A}}\lor {\overline {B}}={\overline {A\cdot B}}$ , making a NAND gate equivalent to inverters followed by an OR gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The NAND gate is significant because any Boolean function can be implemented by using a combination of NAND gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] This property is called "functional completeness".
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] It shares this property with the NOR gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] Digital systems employing certain logic circuits take advantage of NAND's functional completeness.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] NAND gates with two or more inputs are available as integrated circuits in transistor–transistor logic, CMOS, and other logic families.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] There are three symbols for NAND gates: the *MIL/ANSI* symbol, the *IEC* symbol and the deprecated *DIN* symbol sometimes found on old schematics.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The ANSI symbol for the NAND gate is a standard AND gate with an inversion bubble connected.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The function NAND(*a*1, *a*2, ..., *an*) is logically equivalent to NOT(*a*1 AND *a*2 AND ...
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] One way of expressing A NAND B is ${\overline {A\land B}}$ , where the symbol ${\land }$ signifies AND and the bar signifies the negation of the expression under it: in essence, simply ${\displaystyle \lnot (A\land B)}$ .
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The basic implementations can be understood from the image on the left below: If either of the switches S1 or S2 is open, the pull-up resistor R will set the output signal Q to 1 (high).
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] If S1 and S2 are both closed, the pull-up resistor will be overridden by the switches, and the output will be 0 (low).
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] In the depletion-load NMOS logic realization in the middle below, the switches are the transistors T2 and T3, and the transistor T1 fulfills the function of the pull-up resistor.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] In the CMOS realization on the right below, the switches are the n-type transistors T3 and T4, and the pull-up resistor is made up of the p-type transistors T1 and T2, which form the complement of transistors T3 and T4.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] In CMOS, NAND gates are more efficient than NOR gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] This is due to the faster charge mobility in n-MOSFETs compared to p-MOSFETs, so that the parallel connection of two p-MOSFETs (T1 and T2) realised in the NAND gate is more favourable than their series connection in the NOR gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] For this reason, NAND gates are generally preferred over NOR gates in CMOS circuits.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] NAND gates are basic logic gates, and as such they are recognised in TTL and CMOS ICs.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The standard, 4000 series, CMOS IC is the 4011, which includes four independent, two-input, NAND gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] These devices are available from many semiconductor manufacturers.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] These are usually available in both through-hole DIL and SOIC formats.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] Datasheets are readily available in most datasheet databases.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] The NAND gate has the property of functional completeness, which it shares with the NOR gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] That is, any other logic function (AND, OR, etc.) can be implemented using only NAND gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] An entire processor can be created using NAND gates alone.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] In TTL ICs using multiple-emitter transistors, it also requires fewer transistors than a NOR gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/nand-gate] As NOR gates are also functionally complete, if no specific NAND gates are available, one can be made from NOR gates using NOR logic.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In electronic design, a **netlist** is a description of the connectivity of an electronic circuit.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In its simplest form, a netlist consists of a list of the electronic components in a circuit and a list of the nodes they are connected to.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] A network (net) is a collection of two or more interconnected components.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] The structure, complexity and representation of netlists can vary considerably, but the fundamental purpose of every netlist is to convey connectivity information.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Netlists usually provide nothing more than instances, nodes, and perhaps some attributes of the components involved.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] If they express much more than this, they are usually considered to be a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL, or one of several languages specifically designed for input to simulators or hardware compilers (such as SPICE analog simulation netlists).
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Most netlists either contain or refer to descriptions of the parts or devices used.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Each time a part is used in a netlist, this is called an "instance".
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] These descriptions will usually list the connections that are made to that kind of device, and some basic properties of that device.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] These connection points are called "terminals" or "pins", among several other names.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] An "instance" could be anything from a MOSFET transistor or a bipolar junction transistor, to a resistor, a capacitor, or an integrated circuit chip.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In the case of a vacuum cleaner, these terminals would be the three metal prongs in the plug.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Each terminal has a name, and in continuing the vacuum cleaner example, they might be "Neutral", "Live" and "Ground".
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Usually, each instance will have a unique name, so that if you have two instances of vacuum cleaners, one might be "vac1" and the other "vac2".
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Besides their names, they might otherwise be identical.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Networks (nets) are the "wires" that connect things together in the circuit.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] There may or may not be any special attributes associated with the nets in a design, depending on the particular language the netlist is written in, and that language's features.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Instance based netlists usually provide a list of the instances used in a design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Along with each instance, either an ordered list of net names is provided, or a list of pairs provided, of an instance port name, along with the net name to which that port is connected.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In this kind of description, the list of nets can be gathered from the connection lists, and there is no place to associate particular attributes with the nets themselves.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] SPICE is an example of instance-based netlists.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Net-based netlists usually describe all the instances and their attributes, then describe each net, and say which port they are connected on each instance.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] This allows for attributes to be associated with nets.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] EDIF is probably the most famous of the net-based netlists.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In large designs, it is a common practice to split the design into pieces, each piece becoming a "definition" which can be used as instances in the design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In the vacuum cleaner analogy, one might have a vacuum cleaner definition with its ports, but now this definition would also include a full description of the machine's internal components and how they connect (motors, switches, etc.), like a wiring diagram does.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] A definition which includes no instances is called a "primitive" (or a "leaf", or other names); whereas a definition which includes instances is "hierarchical".
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] A "folded" hierarchy allows a single definition to be represented several times by instances.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] An "unfolded" hierarchy does not allow a definition to be used more than once in the hierarchy.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Folded hierarchies can be extremely compact.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] A small netlist of just a few instances can describe designs with a very large number of instances.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] For example, suppose definition A is a simple primitive, like a memory cell.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Then suppose definition B contains 32 instances of A; C contains 32 instances of B; D contains 32 instances of C; and E contains 32 instances of D.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] The design now contains 5 definitions (A through E) and 128 instances.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Yet, E describes a circuit that contains over a million memory cells.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In a "flat" design, only primitives are instanced.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Hierarchical designs can be recursively "exploded" ("flattened") by creating a new copy (with a new name) of each definition each time it is used.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] If the design is highly folded, expanding it like this will result in a much larger netlist database, but preserves the hierarchy dependencies.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Given a hierarchical netlist, the list of instance names in a path from the root definition to a primitive instance specifies the single unique path to that primitive.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] The paths to every primitive, taken together, comprise a large but flat netlist that is exactly equivalent to the compact hierarchical version.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Backannotation is data that could be added to a hierarchical netlist.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Usually they are kept separate from the netlist, because several such alternate sets of data could be applied to a single netlist.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] These data may have been extracted from a physical design, and might provide extra information for more accurate simulations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Usually the data are composed of a hierarchical path and a piece of data for that primitive or finding the values of RC delay due to interconnection.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Another concept often used in netlists is that of inheritance.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Suppose a definition of a capacitor has an associated attribute called "Capacitance", corresponding to the physical property of the same name, with a default value of "100 pF" (100 picofarads).
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] Each instance of this capacitor might also have such an attribute, only with a different value of capacitance.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] And other instances might not associate any capacitance at all.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] In the case where no capacitance is specified for an instance, the instance will "inherit" the 100 pF value from its definition.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] A value specified will "override" the value on the definition.
[src:rtl-synthesis/netlist] If a great number of attributes end up being the same as on the definition, a great amount of information can be "inherited", and not have to be redundantly specified in the netlist, saving space, and making the design easier to read by both machines and people.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In digital circuit design, **register-transfer level** (**RTL**) is a design abstraction which models a synchronous digital circuit in terms of the flow of digital signals (data) between hardware registers, and the logical operations performed on those signals.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Register-transfer-level abstraction is used in hardware description languages (HDLs) like Verilog and VHDL to create high-level representations of a circuit, from which lower-level representations and ultimately actual wiring can be derived.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Design at the RTL level is typical practice in modern digital design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Unlike in software compiler design, where the register-transfer level is an intermediate representation and at the lowest level, the RTL level is the usual input that circuit designers operate on.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In circuit synthesis, an intermediate language between the input register transfer level representation and the target netlist is sometimes used.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Unlike in netlist, constructs such as cells, functions, and multi-bit registers are available.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Transaction-level modeling is a higher level of electronic system design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] A synchronous circuit consists of two kinds of elements: registers (sequential logic) and combinational logic.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Registers (usually implemented as D flip-flops) synchronize the circuit's operation to the edges of the clock signal, and are the only elements in the circuit that have memory properties.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Combinational logic performs all the logical functions in the circuit and it typically consists of logic gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] For example, a very simple synchronous circuit is shown in the figure.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The inverter is connected from the output, Q, of a register to the register's input, D, to create a circuit that changes its state on each rising edge of the clock, clk.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In this circuit, the combinational logic consists of the inverter.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] When designing digital integrated circuits with a hardware description language (HDL), the designs are usually engineered at a higher level of abstraction than transistor level (logic families) or logic gate level.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] In HDLs the designer declares the registers (which roughly correspond to variables in computer programming languages), and describes the combinational logic by using constructs that are familiar from programming languages such as if-then-else and arithmetic operations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This level is called *register-transfer level*.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The term refers to the fact that RTL focuses on describing the flow of signals between registers.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Using an EDA tool for synthesis, this description can usually be directly translated to an equivalent hardware implementation file for an ASIC or an FPGA.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The synthesis tool also performs logic optimization.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] At the register-transfer level, some types of circuits can be recognized.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] If there is a cyclic path of logic from a register's output to its input (or from a set of registers outputs to its inputs), the circuit is called a state machine or can be said to be sequential logic.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] If there are logic paths from a register to another without a cycle, it is called a pipeline.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] RTL is used in the logic design phase of the integrated circuit design cycle.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] An RTL description is usually converted to a gate-level description of the circuit by a logic synthesis tool.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The synthesis results are then used by placement and routing tools to create a physical layout.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Logic simulation tools may use a design's RTL description to verify its correctness.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The most accurate power analysis tools are available for the circuit level but unfortunately, even with switch- rather than device-level modelling, tools at the circuit level have disadvantages like they are either too slow or require too much memory thus inhibiting large chip handling.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The majority of these are simulators like SPICE and have been used by the designers for many years as performance analysis tools.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Due to these disadvantages, gate-level power estimation tools have begun to gain some acceptance where faster, probabilistic techniques have begun to gain a foothold.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] But it also has its trade off as speedup is achieved on the cost of accuracy, especially in the presence of correlated signals.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Over the years it has been realized that biggest wins in low power design cannot come from circuit- and gate-level optimizations whereas architecture, system, and algorithm optimizations tend to have the largest impact on power consumption.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Therefore, there has been a shift in the incline of the tool developers towards high-level analysis and optimization tools for power.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This in no way implies that lower level tools are unimportant.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Instead, each layer of tools provides a foundation upon which the next level can be built.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The abstractions of the estimation techniques at a lower level can be used on a higher level with slight modifications.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] It is a technique based on the concept of gate equivalents.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The complexity of a chip architecture can be described approximately in terms of gate equivalents where gate equivalent count specifies the average number of reference gates that are required to implement the particular function.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The total power required for the particular function is estimated by multiplying the approximated number of gate equivalents with the average power consumed per gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Assign a complexity in terms of gate equivalents.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The number of GE’s for each unit type are either taken directly as an input from the user or are fed from a library.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] is the assumed average dissipated energy by a gate equivalent, when active.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] , denotes the average percentage of gates switching per clock cycle and is allowed to vary from function to function.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] , is a combination of fan-out loading as well as wiring.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] An estimate of the average wire length can be used to calculate the wiring capacitance.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The percentage of gates switching per clock cycle denoted by activity factors are assumed to be fixed regardless of the input patterns.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Typical gate switching energy is characterized by completely random uniform white noise (UWN) distribution of the input data.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] This implies that the power estimation is same regardless of the circuit being idle or at maximum load as this UWN model ignores how different input distributions affect the power consumption of gates and modules.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] denotes the loading due to a single cell hanging off the bit line.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The chosen activity factor gives the correct total power, but the breakdown of power into logic, clock, memory, etc. is less accurate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Therefore this tool is not much different or improved in comparison with CES.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Where Ki is PFA proportionality constant that characterizes the ith functional element $G_{i}$ is the measure of hardware complexity, and $f_{i}$ denotes the activation frequency.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Gi denoting the hardware complexity of the multiplier is related to the square of the input word length i.e.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The activation frequency is the rate at which multiplies are performed by the algorithm denoted by $f_{mult}$ and the PFA constant, $K_{mult}$ , is extracted empirically from past multiplier designs and shown to be about 15 fW/bit2-Hz for a 1.2 μm technology at 5V.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The estimation error (relative to switch-level simulation) for a 16x16 multiplier is experimented and it is observed that when the dynamic range of the inputs does not fully occupy the word length of the multiplier, the UWN model becomes extremely inaccurate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Granted, good designers attempt to maximize word length utilization.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] Still, errors in the range of 50-100% are not uncommon.
[src:rtl-synthesis/register-transfer-level] The figure clearly suggests a flaw in the UWN model.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] In semiconductor design, **standard-cell methodology** is a method of designing application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) with mostly digital-logic features.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Standard-cell methodology is an example of design abstraction, whereby a low-level very-large-scale integration (VLSI) layout is encapsulated into an abstract logic representation (such as a NAND gate).
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Cell-based methodology – the general class to which standard cells belong – makes it possible for one designer to focus on the high-level (logical function) aspect of digital design, while another designer focuses on the implementation (physical) aspect.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Along with semiconductor manufacturing advances, standard-cell methodology has helped designers scale ASICs from comparatively simple single-function ICs (of several thousand gates), to complex multi-million gate system-on-a-chip (SoC) devices.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A standard cell is a group of transistor and interconnect structures that provides a Boolean logic function (e.g., AND, OR, XOR, XNOR, inverters) or a storage function (flipflop or latch).
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Usually, the initial design of a standard cell is developed at the transistor level, in the form of a *transistor netlist* or *schematic* view.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The netlist is a nodal description of transistors, of their connections to each other, and of their terminals (ports) to the external environment.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A schematic view may be generated with a number of different computer-aided design (CAD) or electronic design automation (EDA) programs that provide a graphical user interface (GUI) for this netlist generation process.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Designers use additional CAD programs such as SPICE to simulate the electronic behavior of the netlist, by declaring input stimulus (voltage or current waveforms) and then calculating the circuit's time domain (analog) response.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The simulations verify whether the netlist implements the desired function and predict other pertinent parameters, such as power consumption or signal propagation delay.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Since the logical and netlist views are only useful for abstract (algebraic) simulation, and not device fabrication, the physical representation of the standard cell must be designed too.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Also called the *layout view*, this is the lowest level of design abstraction in common design practice.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] From a manufacturing perspective, the standard cell's VLSI layout is the most important view, as it is closest to an actual "manufacturing blueprint" of the standard cell.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The layout is organized into *base layers*, which correspond to the different structures of the transistor devices, and *interconnect wiring layers* and *via layers*, which join together the terminals of the transistor formations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The *interconnect wiring layers* are usually numbered and have specific *via* layers representing specific connections between each sequential layer.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Non-manufacturing layers may also be present in a layout for purposes of design automation, but many layers used explicitly for place and route (PNR) CAD programs are often included in a separate but similar *abstract* view.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The abstract view often contains much less information than the layout and may be recognizable as a Library Exchange Format (LEF) file or an equivalent.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] After a layout is created, additional CAD tools are often used to perform a number of common validations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A design rule check (DRC) is done to verify that the design meets foundry and other layout requirements.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A parasitic extraction (PEX) then is performed to generate a PEX-netlist with parasitic properties from the layout.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The nodal connections of that netlist are then compared to those of the schematic netlist with a *layout vs schematic* (LVS) procedure to verify that the connectivity models are equivalent.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The PEX-netlist may then be simulated again (since it contains parasitic properties) to achieve more accurate timing, power, and noise models.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] These models are often *characterized* (contained) in a Synopsys Liberty format, but other Verilog formats may be used as well.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Finally, powerful place and route (PNR) tools may be used to pull everything together and *synthesize* (generate) very-large-scale integration (VLSI) layouts, in an automated fashion, from higher level design netlists and floor-plans.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Additionally, a number of other CAD tools may be used to validate other aspects of the cell views and models.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] And other files may be created to support various tools that utilize the standard cells for a plethora of other reasons.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] All of these files that are created to support the use of all of the standard-cell variations are collectively known as a standard-cell library.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] For a typical Boolean function, there are many different functionally equivalent transistor netlists.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Likewise, for a typical netlist, there are many different layouts that fit the netlist's performance parameters.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The designer's challenge is to minimize the manufacturing cost of the standard cell's layout (generally by minimizing the circuit's die area), while still meeting the cell's speed and power performance requirements.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Consequently, integrated circuit layout is a highly labor-intensive job, despite the existence of design tools to aid this process.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A standard-cell library is a collection of low-level electronic logic functions such as AND, OR, NOT, flip-flops, latches, and buffers.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] These cells are realized as fixed-height, variable-width full-custom cells.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The key aspect with these libraries is that they are of a fixed height, which enables them to be placed in rows, easing the process of automated digital layout.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The cells are typically optimized full-custom layouts, which minimize delays and area.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Timing abstract - generally in Liberty format, to provide functional definitions, timing, power, and noise information for each cell.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] An example is a simple XOR logic gate, which can be formed from OR, NOT and AND gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Strictly speaking, a 2-input NAND or NOR function is sufficient to form any arbitrary Boolean function set.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] But in modern ASIC design, standard-cell methodology is practiced with a sizable library (or libraries) of cells.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The library usually contains multiple implementations of the same logic function, differing in area and speed.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] This variety enhances the efficiency of automated synthesis, place, and route (SPR) tools.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Indirectly, it also gives the designer greater freedom to perform implementation trade-offs (area vs. speed vs. power consumption).
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A complete group of standard-cell descriptions is commonly called a *technology library*.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Commercially available electronic design automation (EDA) tools use the technology libraries to automate synthesis, placement, and routing of a digital ASIC.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The technology library is developed and distributed by the foundry operator.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The library (along with a design netlist format) is the basis for exchanging design information between different phases of the SPR process.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Using the technology library's cell logical view, the logic synthesis tool performs the process of mathematically transforming the ASIC's register-transfer level (RTL) description into a technology-dependent netlist.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] This process is analogous to a software compiler converting a high-level C-program listing into a processor-dependent assembly-language listing.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The netlist is the standard-cell representation of the ASIC design, at the logical view level.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] It consists of instances of the standard-cell library gates, and port connectivity between gates.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Proper synthesis techniques ensure mathematical equivalency between the synthesized netlist and original RTL description.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The netlist contains no unmapped RTL statements and declarations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The high-level synthesis tool performs the process of transforming the C-level models (SystemC, ANSI C/C++) description into a technology-dependent netlist.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The placement tool starts the physical implementation of the ASIC.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] With a 2-D floorplan provided by the ASIC designer, the placer tool assigns locations for each gate in the netlist.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The resulting *placed gates* netlist contains the physical location of each of the netlist's standard-cells, but retains an abstract description of how the gates' terminals are wired to each other.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Typically the standard cells have a constant size in at least one dimension that allows them to be lined up in rows on the integrated circuit.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The chip will consist of a huge number of rows (with power and ground running next to each row) with each row filled with the various cells making up the actual design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Placers obey certain rules: Each gate is assigned a unique (exclusive) location on the die map.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] A given gate is placed once, and may not occupy or overlap the location of any other gate.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Using the placed-gates netlist and the layout view of the library, the router adds both signal connect lines and power supply lines.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The fully routed physical netlist contains the listing of gates from synthesis, the placement of each gate from placement, and the drawn interconnects from routing.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Design rule check (DRC) and layout versus schematic (LVS) are verification processes.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Reliable device fabrication at modern deep-submicrometer (0.13 μm and below) requires strict observance of transistor spacing, metal layer thickness, and power density rules.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] DRC exhaustively compares the physical netlist against a set of "foundry design rules" (from the foundry operator), then flags any observed violations.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The LVS process confirms that the layout has the same structure as the associated schematic; this is typically the final step in the layout process.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The LVS tool takes as an input a schematic diagram and the extracted view from a layout.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] It then generates a netlist from each one and compares them.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Nodes, ports, and device sizing are all compared.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] If they are the same, LVS passes and the designer can continue.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] LVS tends to consider transistor fingers to be the same as an extra-wide transistor.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Thus, 4 transistors (each 1 μm wide) in parallel, a 4-finger 1 μm transistor, or a 4 μm transistor are viewed the same by the LVS tool.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The functionality of .lib files will be taken from SPICE models and added as an attribute to the .lib file.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] In semiconductor design, standard cells are ensured to be design rule checking (DRC) and layout versus schematic (LVS) compliant.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] This compliance significantly enhances the efficiency of the design process, leading to reduced turnaround times for designers.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] By ensuring that these cells meet critical verification standards, designers can streamline the integration of these components into larger chip designs, facilitating a smoother and faster development cycle.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] "Standard cell" falls into a more general class of design automation flows called cell-based design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] Structured ASICs, FPGAs, and CPLDs are variations on cell-based design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] From the designer's standpoint, all share the same input front end: an RTL description of the design.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] The three techniques, however, differ substantially in the details of the SPR flow (synthesize, place-and-route) and physical implementation.
[src:rtl-synthesis/standard-cell] For digital standard-cell designs, for instance in CMOS, a common technology-independent metric for complexity measure is gate equivalents (GE).
